{"title_page": "2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Connecticut", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Connecticut\n| country            = Connecticut\n| type               = legislative\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Connecticut\n| previous_year      = 2018\n| next_election      = 2022 United States House of Representatives elections in Connecticut\n| next_year          = 2022\n| seats_for_election = All 5 Connecticut seats to the [[United States House of Representatives]]\n| election_date      = November 3, 2020\n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| last_election1     = 5\n| seats1             = \n| seat_change1       = \n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| swing1             = \n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| last_election2     = 0\n| seats2             = \n| seat_change2       = \n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| swing2             = \n| map_image          = \n| map_caption        = \n}}\n{{Elections in Connecticut}}\nThe '''2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Connecticut''' will be held on November 3, 2020, to elect the five [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representatives]] from the [[U.S. state|state]] of [[Connecticut]], one from each of the state's five [[Connecticut's congressional districts|congressional districts]]. The elections will coincide with the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]], as well as [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2020|other elections]] to the House of Representatives, [[2020 United States Senate elections|elections]] to the [[United States Senate]] and various [[2020 United States elections#State elections|state]] and [[2020 United States elections#Local elections|local elections]].\n{{toclimit|2}}\n\n==District 1==\n{{see also|Connecticut's 1st congressional district}}\nThe incumbent is Democrat [[John B. Larson | John Larson]], who has represented the district since 1999. He was re-elected with 63.9% of the vote in 2018.<ref name=\"HPVT\">{{cite web|last1=Wasserman|first1=David|last2=Flinn|first2=Ally|title=2018 House Popular Vote Tracker|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1WxDaxD5az6kdOjJncmGph37z0BPNhV1fNAH_g7IkpC0/htmlview|publisher=Cook Political Report|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=July 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Declared=====\n* [[John B. Larson | John Larson]], incumbent U.S. Representative<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://larsonforcongress.org|title = Home|date = March 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Primary Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Democratic primary results\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[John B. Larson | John Larson]] (incumbent)\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===General election===\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Connecticut's 1st congressional district results, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[John B. Larson | John Larson]] (incumbent)\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100%\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no change\n| winner = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 2==\n{{see also|Connecticut's 1st congressional district}}\nThe incumbent is Democrat [[Joe Courtney (politician) | Joe Courtney]], who has represented the district since 2007. He was re-elected with 62.2% of the vote in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Munson |first1=Emilie |title=Exclusive: Another Republican joins 5th District race |url=https://www.middletownpress.com/middletown/article/Exclusive-Another-Republican-joins-5th-District-14951820.php |date=January 6, 2020 |accessdate=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Declared=====\n* [[Joe Courtney (politician) | Joe Courtney]], incumbent U.S. Representative\n\n====Primary Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Democratic primary results\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Joe Courtney (politician) | Joe Courtney]] (incumbent)\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Republican primary===\n====Candidates====\n====Declared====\n* Justin Anderson, former Lieutenant Colonel of the [[Connecticut Army National Guard]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://justinandersonforcongress.com/|title=Anderson For Congress - Home|website=justinandersonforcongress.com}}</ref>\n* Thomas Gilmer, commercial roofer<ref name=CT2020>{{Cite news|last1=Radelat|first1=Ana|title=CT Dems attracting early GOP challenges|url=https://ctmirror.org/2019/07/10/ct-dems-attracting-early-gop-challenges|website=The CT Mirror|date=July 10, 2019|accessdate=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Primary Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Justin Anderson\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Thomas Gilmer\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100%\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===General election===\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n|title = Connecticut's 2nd congressional distr